Welp..... Nobody carries these condensers anymore. Online retailers don't have them and local auto stores.

Can any of you guys help me identify this distributor. Somebody told me it's out of an 82 my truck is a 1976.
But I've been trying to find these numbers. In order to find a points replacement setup. A couple people have sent me the hot spark link but I want to make sure that I find the setup that actually fits my distributor.

So if any of you guys are better at this than me I could sure use the help????

Maaan, that was a rough few days.....
I feel like a born again man. Still some congestion and whatnot but today is the first day I'm feeling all right all right. It's Christmas Day we're going to go share some Joy with family and friends I emplore you to do the same.

And if you don't have family or friends you can reach out to me. Nearly everyone is welcome at my table. Tomorrow is where we'll be doing it at my house though I'm going to deep fry a turkey. My world famous way.
So I just like to wish you all a Merry Christmas and a Happy New years. And I'll end up saying that again in another post I'm sure. Find some Joy this next couple of days my friends whatever it takes sometimes that's what the soul needs..

Merry Christmas my friends,

One of the luckiest breaks I ever caught.....
Was adding this family to mine.
I love you @munkys_girl 

Like many folks I know, I have spent a lifetime battling things like depression, battling self doubt, battling poverty, battling the shortcomings of dysfunctional family life.
 I know many of you follow me for the stuff I build. 
If I can give you one piece of advice to you father's out there it's this. And I 100% wish someone had told me this.......

Don't sacrifice these days to go out to your shop and work. No matter what you should break that poor train of thought and go lapend time with your children.
No matter how bad that project or work needs to be done. No matter what!!!!!!!!
 You will never get beck the lost time you didn't spend with your family.......

I didn't know this til it was too late. 
You know my daughter is now grown up in her twenties. And one of the biggest regrets I have is I sacrificed way too much time selfishly in my shop thinking I was doing the right thing trying to get better. Be trying to build my brand or my skills or chasing a stupid dream, When a short amount of times I could have stopped even for a little while and just spent more time with my kid. 
(Don't get me wrong fortunately my kid loves me. Cuz I was not a terrible father)
But deep down I know I always could have done more there. And I regret that

So put the fucking tools down stupid go inside and love your family

I mean if you're actually here to follow me you guys should probably turn on your account notifications. Obviously they throttle me to the point it's fucking ridiculous and I hate @instagram let me clarify I hate the people that work for Instagram they're a bunch of douchebags. The app itself could actually be so much more.

I have 11,000 followers and somehow less than 1, 000 see some of these posts.
At that point it's not about playing algorithms or games or any of that. It quite literally is the discrimination that they claim that they hate or they stand against there is not a bigger group of discriminatory hypocrite people than there are the ones who run these applications. Now with the exception of Twitter. But that's recent

Skid on....... 
I was never a big fan of like a real vertical skid plate. Unless it's real short. And the Valance helps break  it up.

I remember when I was young teens into my twenties... I didn't have anyone to show me how to work on cars  I was raised mainly by my Mom. I didn't have many tools.
I learned mostly by watching the Saturday hot rod shows like @officialstaceydavid  and a few I don't remember the names .
I was naturally mechanically inclined. So I was able to kind of understand quite a bit of it. But very little hands-on experience in my youth...
Little things like how to make your own spark plug wires. I encountered that in my youth and tried to make my own spark plug wires and failed miserably....
Nobody ever really showed me the value of dielectric grease. Small details like that.
I'd say the biggest leap in my personal journey of automotive infatuation. Came with the internet access and forums. That's when I truly started to grow. Access to more information than we ever had........
And nowadays I kind of really miss that era. You know the social media applications are fun to look at stuff. But very lacking in education. But at the same time I have no real desire to go back to the forums. So I feel like we're stuck in a conundrum as far as progression in these industries goes.

I don't know do you guys have any opinions on this stuff what do you think.??????

Last night of my #migwelding course, the day before I have a bunch of pre-cut thin wall tube. That I have them learn to butt weld together and land to flat plate. Representative of exhaust.
But on the final night I set up this weldment. They get 10 chances to kind of learn some circumferential welding that is representative of roll cage tube intersection.. so I notch the tubes. But I show them how to properly clean and bevel their 1/8-in tubing. Then I show them how to start with multiple tacs. With the end goal by the end to being minimal tac points and increased length of stringer. 

I share with them the importance of paying attention to the details. Like out every one of these tubes I will line up the seam in the notcher just so that they are all the same. Simple ideas like that can make worlds of difference in the quality that you bring to the table.....

And this one didn't turn out too bad we got a few things to learn but fortunately I saw some guy do it on TV so I was able to... take their raw parts and turn them into this completed tank. Now we'll send it out for inspection cross our fingers........ 

But if all goes well this will only help our school grow......

So I made an absolute amateur mistake the first time I installed the motor in this car. 
I had inspected the motor..... Including the rear main seal it still felt soft for all intents and purposes appeared correct.................

My theory on how my customer got such a good deal on this motor.........
They built it and drove it but it always pissed oil from the new rear main seal so they sold it. So inside this motor it looked pretty much new. After I put this motor in this car it pissed oil out of the rear main seal. So over the weekend kind of low-key I got some friends to help me. I pulled the motor back out of this car. Pulled the rear main seal apart. Found out that they had installed one of the two part seals backwards. So I went ahead and indexed the seals more appropriately. And then it made sure they're all facing the right direction. Put the motor back in the car got it running again. This thing runs so darn smooth now I am excited that my customer will probably have a nice long lasting motor........ 

But like everybody who already knows this part every vehicle in the future from here on out those seals are being removed and reinstalled or new parts go in. This was stupid on my behalf and embarrassing......

So, here in the @weldors_workshop  I had the opportunity to start building these water purification tanks for a local company. And since I am partnered up with @weldors_supply . Who is a @forneyind dealer. I needed a welder with 4T trigger lock to do the circumferential welds on these tanks. Which I recently switched over to dual shield and that turns it into an approximate 10 minute single stringer. 
So I've run 0.30, 0.35, 0.45 solid core and 0.45 dual shield wire through this machine so far. And it's taking everything I've thrown at it. I also like the wheels on this cabinet with a steel and rubber wheel. 

If you guys are not familiar with @forneyind 
They are one of your legacy welding companies who's been around for almost a hundred years. Their main focus throughout those years was mainly on agricultural and some industrial. However they are beginning to expand their market and inventory of machines. And this is just one of the more heavy duty units.

Finally near complete on this #1954mercury  we did a complete drivetrain Ford 289 with a c4/5 transmission I had my guys at @hdautotransmissions go through, I went through the motor found the rear main seal was backwards and that's why the owner got the motor kind of cheap because they couldn't get it to stop leaking oil.... I had my buddy @johnscustomdrivelines build me a new drive shaft to go with the new drivetrain. We also did a power steering upgrade and a new aftermarket steering column..... Then of course we got into my nightmare which was electrical issues all over, although the owner had one of his buddies prepare it for 12 volt 20 years ago. Some of the wires were so corroded they would snap off the moment you touch them. Some were original wiring that were cloth jackets rotten all the way through where bare wires were touching steel for the headlights and whatnot. I cannot thank @weldors_supply and @afterhoursf150 for saving the day on the wiring. The hard work they put in for me was amazing. You'd think it'd be simple on a car like this but it was a pain in the ass. And those guys stuck it out and made it happen. This car is far from perfect but I drove it on the freeway today and it's so darn cool. It still has a few issues that the owner will you either need me to address or have one of his guys to address. But nonetheless I was stressed on this car and now I'm satisfied so we can send it home with its owner or he can have me do a little bit more we'll see.............

Soooo,  I am thinking on my C10 I am gonna make one side of the tank drop down and mount a factory Chevy fuel pump. The lower plate will get welded to the bottom and those cool aircraft grade titanium thread certs to seal the pump, and give room for the top plate to be a hold down. Then on the other side I might drop it down for the fuel filler neck anyways to match.......

My next querry is,  this will leave me enough room to reach in there so I could just put foam in this tank and be okay. Or should I just do a couple of aluminum baffles and call it a day?

Then once all that's done I'll seal the whole thing up and leak test...

I went to get ready to start bending up my fuel lines.....

Looking all over my shop for my little tube bender  and then I remembered I loaned it to my buddy @afterhoursf150 so he can button up the rear end of his truck....

So I tinkered with a few other things. I've got the hydro boost mostly plumbed power steering mostly plumbed. And then for two years I held on to the power steering cooler floating around the yard. In like 2 months ago I was like oh I'm not going to need this and threw it away and now I can totally use it. Rather than buy a new one LOL

I need a welder helper.......

So I'm looking for a helper for my workshop.
I need somebody to help me build these tanks. This is somewhat of a part-time job that makes good money. The hours are from approximately 11:00 a.m. to 5:00 p.m. Monday through Thursday at a minimum. In banning California
But the pay is per tank. And I want to manufacture two tanks per week at a minimum.

The job is labor intensive inside of my shop. So the ideal candidate for me is going to be somebody Young, driven, willing to learn. You will inherently learn welding and fabricating from me. And there is potential for growth for the right person.

Must be willing to show up every day and be reliable. You would be working with me personally on a daily basis. 

You must know how to read a tape measure and do basic math. You must be somewhat mechanically inclined as those are requirements of the job.

I figured I would post this on my personal page before I post it on the local pages looking for help.

And if your first question is what does it pay you're not the candidate I'm looking for.

This week in Mr Agnew's GMAW 1 class, this is the first full week in the lab. Following last week's focus on classroom fundamentals....

#1We start with lapping buildup passes,
These help the student get familiar with the machine learn some straight line welding.  Both whipped and stringer so they can understand the differences between the two.

#2 the standard T-joint steps into the first fillet weld and how to "climb the wall" learning work and travel angles and how those small adjustments result in pretty major improvements

#3 the next fillet, a Lap joint, and over the years I found that I prefer to also include a corner in that lap joint. So that we can start to break bad habits or form good habits. Learning about wrapping out your corners. Not stopping in your corners and why. Most common place to propagate a crack

#4 what becomes in my opinion the most difficult weldment to learn. Verticle up I share with the students first, multi pass single stringers. Then I also throw a little loop for them and show them how to weave uphill which is pretty fun to do with the mig.....

#5 and the last thing that we will touch on this week how to set up an execute a full pen butt weld aka the groove, how to prep and create a landing and space out your "timers" necessary to achieve full pen...

Then in the final week which will be next week we're going to step down into a much thinner material. And then last couple days will start to focus on both sin and stick tubing representative of say exhaust and structure...........

Well, It may not look like much to the average Joe.....

But to me I see light at the end of an incredibly long tunnel. A tunnel that effectively feels like it's takin me 13 years to travel.

I mean there's still a lot to do I still need a drive shaft and I don't even have the brake lights to go with my brake light wiring yet....

I do got to say that when the original manufacturer of my engine management system effectively failed me as a customer. I have to give credit where credit is due
@summitracing picked up the call. And got what I needed shipped out to me as far as the replacement wiring harnesses go. 
Also picked up my own weather pack style kit started making some of my own connections. Not too difficult but there is a learning curve. And I don't quite have the correct crimper. I think I need to get one but what I do have worked so it's not bad...
I got to do so much electrical over the last year. That I feel a lot better laying this out. Thankful to some friends who have given me much guidance @weldors_supply @pshields77 

Guess what else I learned..... Don't bundle it all up the first timewhile  layin it out like you're going to make it nice .. but there's a strong possibility you will take it apart several times.

The other side of the coin is a lot of people take for granted. The sheer volume of effort that goes into hand building an automobile from the ground up. It is considerably more involved than installing long travel kits and even roll caging vehicles or beam conversions...

There is a time when that name @holleyperformance made me think badass hot rods and automotive enthusiast hoorah

And like I said. I would have loved to have been like a great ambassador. I would have had nothing but good things to say even though I paid full price and everything I received no special treatment from this company.

But this hurt. Take a moment and look into how long I've been attempting to achieve this goal, Lots of small businesses, garage enthusiasts, around the country and the world. All kinds of consumers Would love nothing more than just to root for you as a business and we buy your product so make it what you tell us it is. and make our cars badass. But instead I have to sit on hold for an hour tomorrow cuz we need to talk...........

The @holleyperformance saga cont.....
So yesterday they reached out to me. However I missed that phone call. At my convenience I called back. I was on hold for approximately 25 minutes. Before my call was answered. I will say this is a major improvement from my hour-long wait previously. 
What's on the line I was directed to a technician who was already aware of my situation. And prepared to assist me.

Although I was not at my truck at the time, he walked me through steps that I was able to document. Regarding a bricked ECU. AKA non-responding.
Once I got home with the help of a couple of my friends I was able to get the ECU to respond and then reset.
He also informed me that when doing firmware updates or downloads. You can only use the 3.5 handheld and you must unplug the 7-in or 12-in monitor depending on which one you have. It will not work and will give you major issues if they're both plugged in. I think this should be documented in their instruction manual. As I don't remember seeing it in the instructions.

Nonetheless. I will share with you guys how I feel about this. To me and a current state it feels like @holleyperformance
Has heard many of your complaints and grievances. And it seems like they're working towards addressing these issues. The wait times were improved and the customer service improved.

Now personally I would hope their next step would be getting away from Chinese manufacturing and that kind of low quality of that arena. As it feels like there are major differences between their older product and the new product.

And as you can see from my previous post there are many people who feel like the name @holleyperformance
Used to command a great audience of automotive enthusiasts. And so I would hope that they're working to bring that back. But they did go the extra mile on my behalf and I can appreciate that. I look forward to moving forward and seeing how they progress as a manufacturer as well.

As for me this was a major major milestone. And maybe later I'll throw up another post expressing my absolute joy at the fact that my truck started after so many years.

The last time my personal prerunner ran, was 2009, at the @cleandezert event. What an interesting year that turned out to be... Who remembers that.? What a good time that was man. Bands jammin on the back of an RV. The whole southern California Desert race scene showed to clean the dezert , Amazing off-road trucks to look at and out there to play and fill up dumpsters 
I ended up kind of barely tearing an upper arm mount off the frame.
At the time I had a good job as a welder, I brought my truck home and figured let's cut it up and take it to the next level. Little did I know that the economy would tank. I'd find myself unemployed pretty soon after. But to be honest that's what set me on the journey I've been on.
My daughter was still very young. Single dad. Chasing a stupid fucking dream.
This truck was not even fully paid off yet before I chopped it up. I made it to the finish line on the payments and then I would tow this truck in pieces around with me for the next 10 years. Ups and downs and all arounds. And then after that long I kind of decided that I wanted to take what I had built and apply it to something a little more unique. But still in the family. The cab of the current 66 C10 has a story that fits right in with the rest of this.
About 3 years ago I put out the word that I was looking for a classic truck. One of my close friends had what I needed and traded me. I cut this thing up and started essentially rebuilding the truck with all my old parts. And even then the budget has been incredibly limited.
And here we are My daughter is now agrown adult.
And I still have thousands of dollars to spend on this thing...............
So to get this truck running is monumental to me.

You know 10 years ago. I was in the throes of professional welding. And really trying to bring my personal level up to in essence compete with all of you other welders out there. And it was a good time.With the introduction of first the internet forums and then came social media. It brought this entire industry to a whole new level in my opinion.
Yet I still did not see myself producing the high quality products that I now make.

My product is no longer sharing gratuous images of welds that I put down and essentially the selfish nature of that. (Although I do believe it improved our industry) And i am still in this industry wholeheartedly. And I am more proud now than ever of the product that I produce.
Nowadays I produce the next generation of Weldor's

It has been so fulfilling in my life to see my students. All of which I am incredibly proud of. Many of which went on to lucrative and rewarding careers both men and women. I had a wonderful experience at the other school with a lot of respect for the other instructors and the faculty it was a good experience. And I wouldn't be here today without it.
Some of my classes I may only have two or three students. And sometimes it's 6, It's hard to keep my school full because I have a high turnover mainly because I am focused solely on teaching them how to enter this career field. 

So how do you measure success?
To me success is when one of my students sends me a message or a text or a DM. So these are my hands.....
I've used these to make a living for far too many years to count anymore........
So a little over a month ago I woke up one morning both of my arms were completely asleep. It took several hours for my arms to recover in during that I could feel it literally moving down my arms into my thumbs. ever since then both of my thumbs basically are pins and needles all the time now. And every night both of my arms still fall asleep.
So I broke down went to the VA emergency room. Where they told me I had carpal tunnel..
Then it took a little over a month to get my VA appointment.
So a week ago I saw a nurse at my VA appointment All the blood tests everything comes back pretty solid. I'm in decent health. However now I have what they call neuropathy. It's a nervous system issue. So the drugs they give me have been helping But not 100%. And I have not had a long welding job in the last couple of months I'm a little nervous to see how that will pan out.
Now I also have high blood pressure lol so...... More drugs
So for me it's a diet change. The lifetime of drinking Dr peppers and couple months ago I stopped drinking energy drinks. But I still been drinking sodas. I guess I'm going to have to cut all that out this getting old shit is for the birds man. 
I spent a lifetime feeling pretty invincible. I guess I'm not anymore........

"competition breeds quality"
That's something that my dad said to me when I was a kid. And it really stuck. It's a theory and doctrine that I've grown to embrace. Because it absolutely is true when you remove competition oftentimes you will diminish or watch the quality diminish.

So you guys may have seen @seymourpaint engaging more accounts in our industry and what not. I think that's awesome. You know everybody is using one of the other manufacturers stainless steel paint. Which is fine but in my opinion is so absurdly overpriced that I have no desire whatsoever to even use their product anymore. Plus the fact for that price You still might lose a can to clogging another issues. And when I pay that much money for a single can of paint . I had better be assured that not a single can of paint will go to waste. However it does.

So I contacted #Seymorepaint ask them to send me a couple of choice aerosols to test out. We want to see if you can weld through the stainless steel paint. Of course the weld through primer is always a good idea anyways. So they sent me out a small care package. And I'm going to use it on the next handful of builds and we'll see how it holds up. So far the couple of times I've used it it's been awesome and I'm quite satisfied with the quality that I'm getting at the price point you would get it at.........

Thanks @seymourpaint we're going to test some of this stuff out 🤘🤘

The body has been modified so this is not necessarily a restoration project. It would make a great off-road project. But it's got plenty of life left in it to drive around for the next couple of years. Original 1.8 l,  4 speed manual trans. However with the 31-in tires it makes it very freeway friendly this truck will cruise at 80 mph.

I believe at some point somebody truly love this truck and they had it actually restored completely. Then I have no idea what happened after that. When I climbed underneath this truck when I bought it I was sold at how clean it was underneath and in the engine bay. All over this shows signs of being cared for. Unlike many of the trucks you will find this one is in amazing shape other than the body being modified
All the lights work. Most everything on this truck works when I got it the windshield wipers did work but they stopped a couple months ago and I have not had the chance to mess with them. However it's very easy to work on everything in this truck comes with a manual. And if you're buying it for an off-road project I'll try to throw in some off-road goodies. I had a team ask me for a little bit of assistance as well. So I figured I'd show you guys a little tech tip..

And now I have a team to support during the hammers yay. Right on go get them you guys 🤣

You know I know our friend @morganclarkedesign1 showed you guys the other day a little insert for locating #dzeusfasteners . Then all you got to do is give it a little love tap and it will leave a witness mark for your button location....
sometimes you need to locate your dZeus fasteners But the spring is in your way and your little plug may not fit. And rather than drill out the rivets and drop the springs,  I keep a couple of these Allen head style Dzeus buttons around just for this reason. So it's  an alternative take on what Morgan was showing you the other day... Since I don't do as much sheet metal as these  guys. I don't have near as much tooling. But I can get pretty creative in a pinch.

Trimmed off a little piece of Allen sharpen the head stick it right into the recess of the button. Same theory works great....
